# Performance Evaluation Report

## Project Overview

The objective of this project was to evaluate and optimize machine learning models for house price prediction using a preprocessed housing dataset. Two baseline regression models were trained and compared, followed by hyperparameter tuning using GridSearchCV.

## Models Evaluated

1. Linear Regression
2. Decision Tree Regressor
3. Tuned Decision Tree Regressor

## Evaluation Metrics

The following regression metrics were used:

1. Mean Absolute Error (MAE)
2. Mean Squared Error (MSE)
3. R-squared Score (R²)

## Metric Justification

1. MAE measures the average prediction error.
2. MSE penalizes larger prediction errors.
3. R² indicates how well the model explains the variability of the target variable.

## Results

-----------------------------------------------------
| Model               | MAE   | MSE      | R² Score |
| ------------------- | ----- | -------- | -------- |
| Linear Regression   | 40.39 | 9414.30  | 0.524    |
| Decision Tree       | 35.84 | 13359.74 | 0.324    |
| Tuned Decision Tree | 38.15 | 8870.08  | 0.551    |
-----------------------------------------------------

Hyperparameter Tuning

GridSearchCV was applied to the Decision Tree Regressor using the following parameters:

1. max_depth: [5, 10, 15, 20]
2. min_samples_split: [2, 5, 10]
3. min_samples_leaf: [1, 2, 4]

Best Parameters:

1. max_depth = 5
2. min_samples_split = 10
3. min_samples_leaf = 4

## Conclusion

The baseline Decision Tree model showed poor generalization compared to Linear Regression. After hyperparameter tuning, the Decision Tree achieved the highest R² score of 0.551 and the lowest MSE among all evaluated models. Therefore, the Tuned Decision Tree Regressor was selected as the final model for house price prediction.

